<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does freezer repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most residential freezer repairs run between $130 and $350. A defrost heater, thermostat, or evaporator fan replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor or sealed system work runs higher, and we'll give you an honest assessment of whether the repair makes financial sense for the age and brand of the unit. Full written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My freezer runs but won't get cold enough — what's wrong?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Three most likely causes: a failed defrost system that's allowed frost to build up on the evaporator coils and block airflow, a weakening compressor that can no longer maintain temperature, or a refrigerant leak in the sealed system. In LA's warm climate — especially in unconditioned spaces like garages — a freezer working harder than it was designed for can show these symptoms faster than usual. We diagnose the actual cause before recommending parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is it worth repairing a freezer or should I replace it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It depends on the age of the unit, the brand, and what failed. A defrost heater on a 4-year-old Whirlpool is worth fixing. A compressor on a 15-year-old no-name chest freezer probably isn't. On premium brands like Sub-Zero or Thermador, repair almost always makes more sense than replacement because the unit itself is worth considerably more. We give you a straight answer before writing any repair order — if the numbers don't work, we tell you."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My freezer is in the garage — why does it struggle in summer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An unventilated Los Angeles garage can reach 100–110°F on a summer afternoon. Most residential freezers are rated for ambient temperatures up to 90–95°F — beyond that, the compressor runs continuously trying to maintain 0°F against an ambient environment that's 15–20 degrees above its design limit. The compressor overworks, the condenser can't shed heat, and the freezer gradually loses temperature. Annual condenser coil cleaning and making sure the freezer has adequate clearance around it are the two most effective things you can do. We check both on every garage freezer call."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why is there so much frost and ice buildup in my freezer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Excessive frost inside a freezer almost always means the automatic defrost system isn't running correctly. The defrost heater melts accumulated frost off the evaporator coils on a schedule — when the heater, defrost timer, or defrost thermostat fails, frost builds up until it blocks the coils entirely and airflow stops. The freezer runs constantly but can't circulate cold air. A worn door seal that lets warm, humid air in continuously can also cause frost buildup."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Sub-Zero and built-in column freezers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Sub-Zero column freezers and integrated panel-ready units are among the brands we service most frequently in LA's premium home market. These units require OEM Sub-Zero parts — we source directly from authorized suppliers. We also repair Thermador, Viking, and Miele column and built-in freezers."
