</section>

<!-- 05 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Freezer Not Cold Enough</h3>
        <p>Three most likely causes: a failed defrost system that's allowed frost to block the evaporator coils, a weakening compressor that can no longer maintain 0°F, or a refrigerant leak in the sealed system. The defrost system is by far the most common — and the most affordable to fix. We test each systematically before recommending parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Excessive Frost / Ice Buildup</h3>
        <p>Heavy frost on the interior walls or inside the freezer compartment means the automatic defrost cycle isn't running. The defrost heater melts frost off the evaporator coils on a schedule — when the heater, defrost timer, or defrost thermostat fails, frost accumulates until the coils are completely blocked. A worn door seal admitting humid air is the secondary cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Defrost System Failure</h3>
        <p>The defrost system has three components that can fail independently: the defrost heater (warms the coils), the defrost thermostat (limits how hot the heater gets), and the defrost timer or control board (initiates the cycle). Our technicians test all three before replacing anything — each is a different part and a different cost.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Evaporator Fan Failure</h3>
        <p>The evaporator fan circulates cold air from the coils throughout the freezer. When it fails, the coils stay cold but the air doesn't move — temperatures in the front and on upper shelves rise while the back stays cold. A freezer that's cold near the back but warm in front is almost always the evaporator fan motor.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Compressor Issues</h3>
        <p>A failing compressor runs continuously but can't pull temperature down, or starts and stops with a clicking sound. Compressor work is the higher end of freezer repair — we assess whether it's worth replacing given the age, brand, and cost of the unit before recommending it. On Sub-Zero, Thermador, and Viking, it almost always is.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Seal Deterioration</h3>
        <p>A worn or torn door gasket is a slow-moving problem: warm, humid air enters the freezer on every seal cycle, the compressor works harder, frost accumulates faster, and electricity consumption rises. The gasket is one of the more cost-effective freezer repairs — we carry gaskets for the major brands on the van.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Freezer Making Noise</h3>
        <p>A loud buzzing or rattling from a freezer is usually the evaporator fan motor hitting frost buildup, or the condenser fan motor (near the compressor) running rough. A clicking sound that repeats every few minutes points to the compressor trying and failing to start — usually a bad start relay, which is a quick and inexpensive fix.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Sealed System / Refrigerant</h3>
        <p>A refrigerant leak in the sealed system is the diagnosis when the compressor runs normally but the freezer gradually loses temperature over weeks. This requires EPA 608 certified technicians and proper refrigerant handling — our technicians are certified. It's a more involved repair, but on a high-quality unit it's worth doing correctly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 GARAGE FREEZER SPOTLIGHT -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — The LA Garage Freezer Problem</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why freezers struggle in Southern California garages</h2>
    <p class="lead">This is the freezer issue most LA homeowners don't connect to their garage — and none of the generic repair websites mention it.</p>

    <div class="garage-block">
      <div class="garage-label">🌡️ Southern California Heat &amp; Your Freezer</div>
      <h3>Your garage gets to 100°F. Your freezer was designed for 95°F max.</h3>
      <p>An unventilated Los Angeles garage on a July afternoon regularly reaches 100–110°F. Most residential chest and upright freezers are rated for ambient operating temperatures up to 90–95°F. When ambient temperature exceeds that range, the compressor has to work continuously to maintain 0°F — it can never rest, condenser coils overheat, and the freezer gradually loses the battle.</p>
      <p>The result: food that isn't as frozen as it should be, a compressor that wears out years earlier than expected, significantly higher electricity bills, and eventually a call to us. The freezer wasn't broken — it was being asked to work beyond its design limits. We see this constantly in Burbank, Glendale, Pasadena, and the Valley in summer.</p>
      <p>The solutions aren't complicated: condenser coil cleaning (critical — dirty coils make heat shedding even worse), adequate clearance around the unit, and in some cases a small fan to improve garage ventilation. We check all of these on every garage freezer call and give you specific recommendations for your setup.</p>

      <div class="garage-tips">
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>Clean condenser coils yearly</strong>
          <span>Dust and debris on coils trap heat — in a hot garage, this can push a marginal compressor over the edge</span>
        </div>
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>Clearance matters</strong>
          <span>Freezers need 2–3 inches on all sides for heat dissipation — against a wall in a closed garage is worst case</span>
        </div>
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>Ambient rating check</strong>
          <span>Most residential freezers are rated to 90–95°F ambient. LA garages regularly exceed that in summer</span>
        </div>
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>Garage ventilation helps</strong>
          <span>A small vent fan or cracking the garage door in summer can meaningfully reduce ambient temp</span>
        </div>
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>Garage-rated freezers exist</strong>
          <span>Some brands make units rated to 110°F ambient — worth considering if your garage gets very hot</span>
        </div>
        <div class="garage-tip">
          <strong>We inspect on every call</strong>
          <span>Every garage freezer call includes a coil cleaning and ambient condition assessment</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

