<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Burbank · Whirlpool Chest Freezer (Garage)</div>
        <h3>"Everything is thawing — freezer ran all night but it's 25°F inside"</h3>
        <p>Classic garage freezer scenario in August: the chest freezer in an unventilated Burbank garage was fighting ambient temperatures of 105°F+. The condenser coils were heavily coated with dust and pet hair — in a hot garage, clogged coils mean the compressor can't shed heat at all. The compressor was still functional but operating at its limit.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Deep-cleaned condenser coils, verified start relay was functioning correctly, checked door gasket for gaps (found a small worn section — replaced). Moved the freezer 3 inches from the wall to restore clearance. Temperature stabilized at 0°F within two hours. Advised customer on summer garage ventilation — the coils will need annual cleaning going forward.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Bel Air · Sub-Zero 700TF Column Freezer</div>
        <h3>"Frost building up inside — getting worse every week"</h3>
        <p>Defrost heater failure on a Sub-Zero 700TF column freezer. The automatic defrost cycle had stopped running — frost was accumulating on the evaporator coils until the back wall was completely coated. The unit was running continuously but airflow was nearly blocked. Left another few weeks, it would have stopped cooling entirely.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced defrost heater assembly and defrost thermostat (we replace both when one fails — the thermostat failure is what typically causes the heater to fail) with OEM Sub-Zero parts. Manually defrosted the coils before reassembly. Ran two defrost cycles to confirm the system was operating correctly. Unit back to normal temperature and frost-free.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Glendale · LG French Door Bottom Freezer</div>
        <h3>"Freezer is fine near the back but warm in front — ice cream is soft"</h3>
        <p>Evaporator fan motor failure — textbook presentation. The coils at the back of the freezer stay cold because they're right next to the evaporator, but without a working fan, cold air doesn't circulate to the front of the drawer. Ice cream near the front softens; items at the back stay frozen. Easy to diagnose once you know the pattern.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced evaporator fan motor with OEM LG part. Tested airflow distribution across the full freezer compartment before closing up. Even temperature throughout confirmed within 30 minutes of repair. 45-minute total job.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · Samsung RF28 French Door</div>
        <h3>"Freezer is clicking every few minutes and not freezing"</h3>
        <p>Failed start relay — a small but critical component that gives the compressor an initial electrical boost when it tries to start. When the relay fails, the compressor attempts to start, can't, kicks off, and tries again in a few minutes — producing the rhythmic clicking. The compressor itself was fine. This is one of the more satisfying repairs: $40 part, 20 minutes, freezer fully restored.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced start relay with OEM Samsung part. Verified compressor started cleanly on next cycle. Temperature pulled down to 0°F within the hour. Customer had been without a working freezer for three days — was relieved it wasn't the compressor.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
