<!-- 11 FAQ -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Freezer repair — what people ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does freezer repair cost in Los Angeles?</h3>
        <p>Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most residential freezer repairs run between $130 and $350. A defrost heater, thermostat, or evaporator fan replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor or sealed system work runs higher — we give you a written estimate before any work begins and an honest assessment of whether the repair makes sense for your unit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My freezer runs but won't get cold enough — what's wrong?</h3>
        <p>Three most likely causes: a failed defrost system that's allowed frost to block the evaporator coils, a weakening compressor, or a refrigerant leak. In LA's warm climate — especially in unconditioned garage spaces — a freezer working harder than it was designed for shows these symptoms faster. We diagnose the actual cause before recommending parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is it worth repairing a freezer or should I replace it?</h3>
        <p>It depends on the age, brand, and what failed. A defrost heater on a 4-year-old Whirlpool is worth fixing. A compressor on a 15-year-old basic chest freezer probably isn't. On Sub-Zero, Thermador, and Viking, repair almost always makes more sense because the unit itself is worth considerably more. We give you a straight answer before writing any repair order.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My freezer is in the garage — why does it struggle in summer?</h3>
        <p>An unventilated LA garage can reach 100–110°F in summer. Most residential freezers are rated for ambient temperatures up to 90–95°F. Above that, the compressor runs continuously and can never rest. Annual condenser coil cleaning and adequate clearance around the unit are the two most effective things you can do. We check both on every garage freezer call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is there so much frost and ice buildup in my freezer?</h3>
        <p>Excessive frost means the automatic defrost system isn't running correctly. The defrost heater melts accumulated frost off the evaporator coils on a schedule — when the heater, timer, or thermostat fails, frost builds up until it completely blocks the coils. A worn door seal admitting humid air is the secondary cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair Sub-Zero and built-in column freezers?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Sub-Zero column freezers and integrated panel-ready units are among the brands we service most frequently in LA's premium home market. We source OEM Sub-Zero parts directly from authorized suppliers. We also repair Thermador, Viking, and Miele column and built-in freezers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does the 90-day warranty cover on freezer repairs?</h3>
        <p>Every freezer repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

